<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=97198740028885></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f97198740028885><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97198740028885>Repost of a useless Magician Guide</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97198740028885#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1517><span id=Scholar>Elrique</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>17 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Oct 19th 4:30 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hail and G'Day all! <br><br>I posted this quite a while back, and it disappeared, and when I redid the filter, saw that 1 person rated it and it dropped off the list...  Reposting so others get a chance to make up their minds...   :)<br><br>I was a bit leary to post any sort of guide here, after looking at some of the flames other posters have received for their comments/guides, but what the heck... No one knows it all, and my ideas might spark someone else's creativity. <br><br>Breaking this into 3 seperate parts, starting out, soloing and grouping, since there are differing tactics for each type of hunting. <br><br>Starting out: <br><br>Intellegence is directly proportional to mana. The higher your int, the more mana you have per level, until you hit 200 int. Then, it's time to start swapping int items for better and throwing in some mana items or other stat buffing items. This being said, I would recommend anyone starting a Magi to dump as many points as racially possible into Intellegence and then split what few remain across the other stats as you see fit. (Other stats can be raised via items as you gain in levels... Remember, out of mana=dead!) <br><br>That said, the next important thing is mana conservation. If you don't learn it early, you are going to get frustrated and quit, or never reach the potential that you COULD reach by learning this. <br><br>Solo: <br><br>For starting levels, there really isn't much that can be taught... From 1-4 you are petless, and having to rely on melee and a couple of casts to kill those mobs. After that, here are some tricks: <br><br>1) If you are pulling to the pet, in an outdoor situation, where you are controlling what you fight and when you fight it, always put your pet on guard. He always turns to the nearest mob, and can be used as a proximity detector. <br><br>2) Pet control. Always know where your pet is. If you haven't parked him someplace, then he should be right on your tail, if he's not, you are going to be in trouble, sooner or later. <br><br>3) When the money starts to flow in a bit, start carrying more than a few Reagents at a time. You can then setup shop in your hunting grounds, Summon a pet, and then sic him on a green to see the damage he does. If it's not the highest, or the pet cons green, etc... Resummon. (This can take SEVERAL resummons) Always use Reclaim on the pets you are getting rid of in this way, or you will be OOM in just a few tries. <br><br>4) Pets and healing. We have 2 heal spells aimed at pets. One at 8th level and another at 20th level. If your pet is taking a lot of damage, you need to learn when it's time to cut and run, or time to get off that last quick heal, or time to nuke the mob. This takes practice and experience, so keep trying. Remember, your pet is your only friend while soloing. He's the only thing you have to count on, so keep him healthy, and he'll keep you healthy. Kill him off, and you're dead! <br><br>5) If the pull or pet has gotten away from you, count on either zoning or dying. There is no middle ground. He will be back, and with a lot of friends. If your pet doesn't come back, that means there are some majorly upset mobs out there, with your name on their tongues... <br><br>6) Always, always, always put a damage shield on your pet before you go out looking, unless it's a Fire pet. (Remember this is unresisted damage!) Then, when you get back, you don't have to<br>remember to do it, and you can concentrate on killing the mob. <br><br>6) Burnout series. Man, it's so surprising to me the Magi out there that have no clue how this spell series works. What is a good pet without the Burnout series is truely an AWESOME pet with it... If you aren' using it, quit playing the class and try something else, cuz you are wasting your time. <br><br>7) Malise:  This is another complete surprise to me..  We are one of the best at removing a mob's resistances, yet few Magi's seem to use this spell series!  This line is my pulling spell for mobs that aren't casters, or sitting near casters.  Then I pull with the Cancel Magic line..  I use less mana in the long run, by not needing the 3 nukes to get the damage done, when 2 would have done it with full hits...<br><br>Grouping: <br><br>1) Unresistable Damage: Magi's have the best Damage Shields in the game with our Flame Sheilds. When the puller says "inc" it's time to start laying these on the tanks and your pet. (assuming not a Fire pet) The damage might SEEM small, but at 20 points a pop for a 45th level Magi, and assuming the tank gets hit 5 times a tic, that's 100 points of damage that someone doesn't have to do any other way... :) <br><br>2) Maximizing Damage: The Malise line of spells are probably the least used of all the debuffing spells int he game, yet are probably some of the better spells we Magi could ever hope for. How many of us have seen that mob down to the last sliver of health, and you're burning your last sliver of mana, and the pet's almost gone, to see the fatal line "a Mobxx has resisted your xyz spell" <br><br>When I'm pulling, I use Malise/Malisement. Not only does it affect my spell success rates, but also the pet's spells... And any other caster in your group will apreciate seeing that line "Elrique says to the group 'Malise'" <br><br>3) Mana control: Some of the Magi's I've played with are Nuke, Nuke, Nuke, Oom... Now either the rest of the group is carrying the Magi, with a little help from his pet, or, they are waiting for him to get some reserves back up and not maximizing their time killing mobs. Learn when to over burn, and when to sit and med through a fight. <br><br>4) Pets and Healing. I have gotten into the habit of giving mana reports and pet health reports at the same time... Mine are like 60, pet 100. Just a good practice to get into, since that way everyone in the group has a better picture of overall group health. (That one big pull one time the pet's going to be at 20 when the inc comes, and bingo! Dead group, cuz you didn't have the time needed to trim the odds down with a FOH pet.) <br><br>5) Assisting: Always, always, always assist the designated player... (Making an /Assist so-and-so key for this is a great idea.) If your pet is getting hit from another source and continuously reagros on that source, it's time to let the designated assist know which mob and that's the next one on his list. (Tanks might want to make an /Assist pet key so they can get onto the pet's target quicker, too...) <br><br>Many of these things are "Common Sense" but it is SO surprising how many higher level Magis I see running around not doing these things. (Actually, it's almost frightening when I'm grouped with one of them!) :( Just a little bit of time to learn and practice some of these skills are going to be well worth your time and effort in the long run, and will make you a better player as well... Yeah, you might not be soloing to 50 in 3 weeks or less, you WILL be enjoying the time you are in perhaps a bit more by knowing you are a valued part of a group, and doing something together that none of you could do seperately. <br><br>&nbsp;<br>Elrique Melnebone<br>Elementalist of Blood and Honor<br>Master Vending Machine<br>Veeshan</td></tr>
