<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=97560561521815></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f97560561521815><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97560561521815>RE: Where do I find these?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=97560561521815#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Nov 30th 12:33 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have never been a fan of the fire pet.  True, they have hands-down the best fire shield (damage = level + 1!), but the catch is, THE FIRE PET NEEDS TO GET HIT.  Those fire pets are weakly armored, and low on the hit points, so if you are fighting anything decent while soloing, expect your main priority to be healing your pet.  Next thing you know, you'll notice the mana output for healing your pet is equaling the same for nuking.  Not to mention your pet risking death...<br><br>My solo pet of choice would be the water pet.  It helps you learn at what point you are overnuking (ie, the mob turns to YOU now) which is a VALUABLE thing to learn!  And with the water pets agility and troll-like regen, you don't have to watch it too much, which frees you up for things like meditating in the middle of combat. :)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
